VI. - On reaching the shores of Cumae, Aeneas makes his way to the temple of Apollo to consult the sibyl Deiphobe. ln response to his appeal ior aid, she gives him directions tor finding the golden bough which is to be his passport in the under world, and, when he has found it, accompanies him on his journey thither. Having offered due sacrifices to the gods ol the lower world, they enter together the mouth ol the cavemous passage which leads to the realms ol Pluto. Pass- ing on their way the shadowy forms of many monsters of appalling aspect, they reach at length the river Styx, and are ierried over its waters by the grisly Charon. Beyond the Styx they find three distinct areas or enclosures: a neutral region including the Fields of Mourning, Tartarus the place ol tor- ment, and Elysium the abode ol the blest. ln Elysium Anchises dwells Here the sight of the river Lethe and ol the vast multitude ol spirits that are thronging to drink ol its waters leads Anchises to unfold to Aeneas the mysteries of expiation and the transmigration oi souls. They go on and ascend an eminence overlooking the moving host, and here

Anchises points out to Aeneas his future descendants, as they pass in review, and acquaints him with their destiny. The long line of distinguished Romans includes Augustus Caesar, and closes with the young Marcellus, whose early promise and recent death were fresh in the memories of Vergil’s contempo raries. At length, by the ivory gate ot exit, Aeneas returns to the upper world and rejoins his companions.
